    <section class="section" id="appA">
      <span class="chapter-label">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>🧬 The Peptide Supply Chain</h2>
      <p class="chapter-sub"><em>Know Where It Comes From</em></p>
      <p>One of the least talked about — but most important — parts of peptides is where they actually come from. There's a lot of marketing noise in this space, so the goal here isn't to scare you or make you cynical. It's to help you see the landscape clearly so you can make wise, informed decisions.</p>

      <h3>The Big Picture</h3>
      <p>Most research peptides in the world are manufactured overseas. That's not a secret — it's just reality.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>China produces the vast majority of global research peptides</li>
        <li>The U.S. is primarily involved in importing, testing, repackaging, and reselling</li>
        <li>Europe manufactures some peptides, usually at a higher cost</li>
        <li>India is an emerging manufacturing hub</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Very few companies actually synthesize peptides domestically, mainly because it's extremely expensive to do so.</p>

      <h3>How Peptides Typically Move</h3>
      <div class="chain">
        <div class="chain-node">Factory</div>
        <div class="chain-arrow">→</div>
        <div class="chain-node">Importer</div>
        <div class="chain-arrow">→</div>
        <div class="chain-node">Research Co.</div>
        <div class="chain-arrow">→</div>
        <div class="chain-node">You</div>
      </div>
      <p>Sometimes there's one less step, sometimes one more — but that's the basic flow. What matters isn't how many hands touch it, but what happens at each step.</p>

      <h3>Manufacturing Reality</h3>
      <p>Here's the nuance most people miss: <strong>"Made in China" doesn't automatically mean low quality.</strong> There are excellent labs overseas using modern equipment, legitimate quality control, export certifications, and consistent manufacturing standards. There are also bad actors — just like anywhere else.</p>
      <p>Quality issues usually come from: poor or nonexistent QC, fake or recycled COAs, inconsistent batches, or contamination risks. The difference isn't geography — it's standards and verification.</p>

      <h3>The Truth About "U.S. Manufacturers"</h3>
      <p>Most U.S.-based peptide companies are not synthesizing peptides from scratch. They are importing, repackaging, relabeling, sometimes testing, and marking up significantly. That doesn't make them bad — but it does mean the label alone doesn't tell the whole story.</p>

      <h3>Why Prices Vary So Wildly</h3>
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Price Reality</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Factory</td><td>Low cost</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Wholesale / Import</td><td>Moderate increase</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Research Company</td><td>Higher markup</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Clinic / Med-Spa</td><td>Exponentially higher</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>Red Flags to Watch For</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Claims of "U.S. manufactured" with prices that don't add up</li>
        <li>No clarity on sourcing or testing</li>
        <li>Inconsistent results between batches</li>
        <li>COAs that look identical across different suppliers</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="callout">🙏 <strong>The Pastor's Takeaway:</strong> This isn't about becoming paranoid. It's about becoming informed. Peptides are tools. Like any tool, their effectiveness depends on quality, sourcing, and discernment.</div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="appB">
      <span class="chapter-label">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>📖 What Peptides Actually Are</h2>
      <p class="chapter-sub"><em>Research Peptides 101</em></p>
      <p>When most people hear the phrase <em>research peptides</em>, their mind jumps to something sketchy or underground. In reality, research peptides are exactly what the name implies: peptides sold for research purposes. The confusion doesn't come from what they are — it comes from how little the system is explained.</p>

      <h3>What Peptides Actually Are</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Short chains of amino acids, usually between 2 and 50</li>
        <li>Naturally occurring in your body already</li>
        <li>Signaling molecules that tell cells what to do</li>
        <li>Smaller than proteins, but often working in similar ways</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Your body runs on signals. Peptides are part of that internal communication system. For the long version, see <a href="/guides/what-are-peptides">What Are Peptides?</a> in the Gray Market.</p>

      <h3>Research vs. Pharmaceutical: The Real Difference</h3>
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th></th><th>Research Peptides</th><th>Pharmaceutical</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Label</strong></td><td>"Not for human consumption"</td><td>FDA-approved, prescribed</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Cost</strong></td><td>Significantly lower</td><td>Often hundreds/month</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Approval</strong></td><td>Not FDA-approved</td><td>Full regulatory pathway</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Quality</strong></td><td>Depends on sourcing &amp; testing</td><td>Standardized manufacturing</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>The difference is not the molecule — it's the regulatory pathway, labeling, and distribution. The <em>same molecular compound</em> that might cost hundreds per month through a clinic can often be found at a fraction of the price through a research supplier. Same peptide. Different label. Different overhead.</p>

      <h3>Why This Lives in a Gray Zone</h3>
      <p><strong>Science moves faster than regulation.</strong> Many peptides are well-studied at the molecular level, but formal FDA approval is slow, expensive, and usually driven by pharmaceutical companies with financial incentive to pursue it.</p>
      <p><strong>Labeling matters more than chemistry.</strong> The same molecule can exist in two worlds: one regulated and prescribed, the other labeled strictly for research.</p>
      <p><strong>Economics play a role.</strong> Clinics and med-spas carry significant overhead. Research suppliers don't operate in the same system, which creates dramatic price differences for the same compound.</p>
      <p><strong>Education is fragmented.</strong> Most people are never taught how peptides work, how they're regulated, or how to evaluate sourcing. When understanding is low, confusion fills the gap.</p>
      <div class="callout">🙏 <strong>The Pastor's Take:</strong> This isn't about bypassing medicine or rejecting doctors. It's about understanding the system well enough to ask better questions. Clarity always comes first. From there, wiser decisions follow.</div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="appC">
      <span class="chapter-label">Appendix C</span>
      <h2>📖 Terminology</h2>
      <p class="chapter-sub"><em>Words the Congregation Should Know</em></p>
      <p>One of the biggest barriers to using peptides wisely isn't access — it's language. This section exists to remove that friction. No hype, no intimidation — just clear definitions.</p>

      <h3>Core Terms</h3>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>Lyophilized</strong><span>Freeze-dried powder. How most peptides arrive — stable for storage and shipping.</span></div>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>Reconstitution</strong><span>Adding liquid (BAC water) to the powder so it's ready to use.</span></div>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>COA (Certificate of Analysis)</strong><span>A lab report showing purity, potency, and quality markers. Non-negotiable.</span></div>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>mg vs. mL</strong><span>Milligrams (mg) = amount. Milliliters (mL) = volume. Mixing these up is the #1 beginner mistake.</span></div>

      <h3>Dosing &amp; Administration</h3>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>mcg (micrograms)</strong><span>A smaller unit. 1,000 mcg = 1 mg.</span></div>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>IU (International Units)</strong><span>Used for compounds like growth hormone. Not interchangeable with mg.</span></div>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>SubQ (Subcutaneous)</strong><span>Injection just under the skin. Most common method for peptides.</span></div>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>IM (Intramuscular)</strong><span>Injection into the muscle. Less common, used for specific compounds.</span></div>

      <h3>Quality &amp; Stability</h3>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>Purity</strong><span>Percentage of the vial that's actually the peptide. 98%+ is solid.</span></div>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>Sterility</strong><span>Whether the peptide is free from bacteria or contamination.</span></div>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>Potency</strong><span>How effective the peptide is based on concentration and integrity.</span></div>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>Stability</strong><span>How well the peptide holds up over time before and after mixing.</span></div>

      <h3>Common Points of Confusion</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>A "10 mg vial" refers to the amount of peptide <em>powder</em> — not how much liquid is inside</li>
        <li>"99% purity" means 99% of the powder is the intended peptide, not filler</li>
        <li>Bacteriostatic water is sterile water with a preservative that prevents bacterial growth after mixing</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Supplier &amp; Business Terms</h3>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>MOQ (Minimum Order Quantity)</strong><span>The smallest amount a supplier will sell.</span></div>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>NET 30</strong><span>Payment is due 30 days after invoicing — for business accounts.</span></div>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>Wholesale</strong><span>Bulk pricing for resellers or clinics.</span></div>
      <div class="term-block"><strong>Drop Shipping</strong><span>The supplier ships directly to the customer instead of through the seller.</span></div>

      <h3>Marketing Language to Treat with Caution</h3>
      <div class="warn-card"><strong>"Pharma grade"</strong> — Not a regulated or meaningful designation in this space.</div>
      <div class="warn-card"><strong>"Human grade"</strong> — Marketing language, not a standard.</div>
      <div class="warn-card"><strong>"FDA approved"</strong> — Research peptides are not FDA-approved.</div>
      <div class="warn-card"><strong>"Guaranteed results"</strong> — A major red flag. Walk away.</div>
    </section>

